				\begin{document}$${\mathfrak {f}}\ge 0$$\end{document}), the set generated by the normalized moments {1,h,k,q}\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\{\,1,\,{\mathfrak {h}},\,{\mathfrak {k}},\,{\mathfrak {q}}\,\}$$\end{document} is convex and bounded, which in turn allows one to construct any sequence of moments in this set by a convex combination of moment vectors on the boundary of this domain. The moments constructed by this procedure are then “good” in the sense that they can be obtained from a nonnegative distribution function.

